\layout Subsection

The Polynomials 
\layout Standard

The action of a group element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 on the Takagi curve can be written as 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}(\gamma_{D}(x))=p_{\gamma}(w)+x\, q_{\gamma}(w)+w^{M_{\gamma}}t_{w}(x)\]

\end_inset 

 for some polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 and positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 where we use the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 to denote that they depend on the particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 chosen.
 A brief bit of scratching shows what the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 polynomial is; but 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 is harder.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r...rg^{a_{N}}$
\end_inset 

 as before, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\gamma}=a_{1}+...+a_{N}$
\end_inset 

.
 Next, we write out the binary expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}(1)$
\end_inset 

 in terms of binary digits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset 

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\gamma_{D}(1) & = & \sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{b_{k}}{2^{k}}\\
\, & = & \begin{array}{ccccc}
0. & \underbrace{000...000} & \underbrace{111...111} & \underbrace{000...000} & ...\\
\, & a_{1} & a_{2} & a_{3} & \,\end{array}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 where, as usual, we take the expansion such that the final binary digits
 repeat forever, without upsetting the count 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}$
\end_inset 

 of the previous digits; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
b_{k}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \;\textrm{ for N odd, }\; & \forall k>M\\
0 & \;\textrm{ for N even, }\; & \forall k>M\end{array}\right.\]

\end_inset 

 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 can then be expressed directly in terms of this binary expansion.
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
q_{\gamma}(w)=\frac{(-)^{N}}{2^{M-1}}\sum_{k=1}^{M}(2b_{k}-1)\;(2w)^{k-1}\]

\end_inset 

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 is more-or-less equal to (up to a factor and a term of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(1-2w)$
\end_inset 

) the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dt_{w}(x)/dx\;|\, x=\gamma_{D}(1)$
\end_inset 

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

more or less
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 because some care has to be taken to define which bit expansion defines
 the derivative.
 In a certain sense, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

