 With a minimum of effort, one can quickly see that these curves transform
 in a fashion similar to the Takagi Curve.
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $g,$
\end_inset 

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[g\phi_{z,l}\right](x)=\left[\phi_{z,l}g\right](x)=\phi_{z,l}(\frac{x}{2})=\exp\left((2l+1)\pi ix\right)+z\phi_{z,l}(x)\]

\end_inset 

 and for reflection,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[r\phi_{z,l}\right](x)=\left[\phi_{z,l}r\right](x)=\phi_{z,l}(1-x)=\phi_{z,l}(-x)\]

\end_inset 

 Concatenating group elements proceeds in a fashion similar to before.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{D}^{3}r_{D}g_{D}^{2}(x)=\frac{1}{8}-\frac{x}{32}\]

\end_inset 

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[g^{3}rg^{2}\phi_{z}\right](x)=\phi_{z}\left(\frac{1}{8}-\frac{x}{32}\right)=\exp\left(i\pi\left(\frac{1}{4}-\frac{x}{16}\right)\right)+z\phi_{z}\left(\frac{1}{4}-\frac{x}{16}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 where we've taken, for convenience, 
\begin_inset Formula $l=0$
\end_inset 

.
 Peeling off one group element at a time, we finally get 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi_{z}\left(\frac{1}{8}-\frac{x}{32}\right)=\exp\left(i\pi\left(\frac{1}{4}-\frac{x}{16}\right)\right)+z\,\exp\left(i\pi\left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{x}{8}\right)\right)+\]

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \[
\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;+z^{2}\exp\left(i\pi\left(1-\frac{x}{4}\right)\right)+z^{3}\exp\left(-i\pi\frac{x}{2}\right)+z^{4}\exp\left(-i\pi x\right)+z^{5}\phi_{z}\left(-x\right)\]

\end_inset 

 However, this obscures the true form of the transformation, which is exhibited
 more clearly if we write the above as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{3}rg^{2}\phi_{z}=\phi_{z}g^{3}rg^{2}=Eg^{3}rg^{2}+z\, Eg^{2}rg^{2}+z^{2}Egrg^{2}+z^{3}Erg^{2}+z^{4}Erg+z^{5}\phi_{z}r\]

\end_inset 

 where we defined 
\begin_inset Formula $E(x)\equiv\exp(2\pi ix)$
\end_inset 

.
 Just to be perfectly clear, in the above expression, we mean functional
 composition whenever two elements are next to each other, with the exception
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

, which is just plain multiplication.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset 

 has the effect of peeling off one group element at a time, and converting
 it to a 
\begin_inset Formula $z.$
\end_inset 

 The result is a funny polynomial which captures the action of the group
 element.
 The funny polynomial is the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{z}$
\end_inset 

 under the action of a general group element.
 We abstain from trying to write the corresponding polynomial for the general
 element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r...rg^{a_{N}}$
\end_inset 

 mostly because it would be quite ungainly.
 We note only that the highest power of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}+a_{2}+...+a_{N}$
\end_inset 

 and also that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 can take the place of a minus sign, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Er)(x)=E(r(x))=E(1-x)=E(-x)$
\end_inset 

, which remains in place, until the next 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 cancels it out.
 None-the-less, this polynomial is curious, and calls for further development.
 
